Red Wine Exploratory Data Analysis by R

Anouar Zbaida

nov 28, 2017

Introduction

In this project we will explores the univariate, bivariate, & multivariate relationships between variables using exploratory data analysis (EDA) techniques in R. To do so we are going to use a tidy data that is created - using red wine samples - on 2009 by P.cortez and al, the dataset is related to variants of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine.

About the dataset

This dataset is public available for research. The details are described in [Cortez et al., 2009].

P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

Available at:

  • Elsevier
  • Pre-press (pdf)
  • bib

Variable description

  • Fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)
  • Volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste
  • Citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines
  • Residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet
  • Chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine
  • Free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine
  • Total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine
  • Density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content
  • pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale
  • Sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant
  • Alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine
  • Quality: output variable (based on sensory data, score between 0 and 10)

Variable information

Input variables (based on physicochemical tests):

  • fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3)
  • volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3)
  • citric acid (g / dm^3)
  • residual sugar (g / dm^3)
  • chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3
  • free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
  • total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3)
  • density (g / cm^3)
  • pH
  • sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3)
  • alcohol (% by volume)

Output variable (based on sensory data):

  • quality (score between 0 and 10)

Exploring Data

Loading up libraries for project

  • ggplot2 : Needed for graphs
  • dplyr: Needed for data manipulation functions
  • gridExtra: Allows multiple graphs in a single grid
  • reshape: used for melt and cast functions (data aggregation)
  • RColorBrewer: Creates nice looking color palettes especially for thematic maps
  • lattice: an implementation of Trellis graphics for R
  • scales: Generic plot scaling methods
  • memisc: This package collects an assortment of tools that are intended to make work with R easier
  • reshape: melt and cast functions (data aggregation)
  • sandwich: Constructing sandwich covariance matrix estimators by multiplying bread and meat matrices
  • graphics: functions for ‘base’ graphics

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The Red Wine Dataset had 1599 observations with 13 variables. All the variables are numerical, expect for quality, which is an categorical. The categorical variable indicate the quality of the wine, at least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, and rated it between 0 (bad) and 10 (excellent).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

By univariate analysis, we could notice :

  • 82.5% of the wines are rated either a 5 or 6
  • Most wines have an alcohol content of less than 11%
  • 34% fixed.acidity values between [7,8] and 78% Citric.acid values below 0.5
  • pH and density are the most normally distributed features
  • Residual sugar, chlorides, sulphates all have big outliers

We want to analyse the quality, so quality is the main feature of interest.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Unsure how the multiple acidity variables relate to each other and quality. We notice that Citric.acid is the only variable with observations equal to zero. And we think sulphates, chlorides may help to analyse the quality of wine as well.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes, we changed quality to an ordered factor and created a new variable called “rating”" to classifying wines as bad, average or good based on quality.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

  • Citric acid has a unique distribution as compared to the other numeric variables. It almost has a rectangular shape apart from a few outliers
  • More than 80% rathed between 5 and 6, so this less informations will make it hard to go out with a good result
  • Tidy adjustments not made to data
  • Change the quality type into an ordered feature

Multivariate Plots Section

In this section we are going to create a few multivariate plots to investigate more complex interactions between the variables that are most related to quality of the wine. Then we willcreate some mathematical models.

These scatterplots were crowded since more than 80% have average quality, so we faceted by rating. It is now more clear that higher quality wines tend to be higher in alcohol, citric acid and sulphates. On the other hand, higher quality wines tend to be lower in volatile acidity.

Reflection

Through this exploratory data analysis of red wine dataset, We can assume how domain knowledge is helpful during the process. We could reveals the key factor affecting the quality of wine, mainly: alcohol, sulphates, and volatile acidity even tough we had a limited data of 1599 observations. In that dataset 82% of the wines are of avergae quality betwen 5 & 6. If we could have a dataset of more observations and an uniform quality of wines. Then we will be able to perform a better analysis.

The linear model which we have used for the prediction is not a good model as its coefficient of determination was very low. For the further study we would try differnt modeling technic; it might give more accuracy.

Opening to more reseach for the reader

Receiving Operating Characteristic, or ROC, is a visual way for inspecting the performance of a binary classifier (0/1). This is just a test, and our binary classifier for this dataset is if the quality more than 5 (1), or less than 5 (0). We are comparing the rate at which our classifier is making correct predictions (True Positives or TP) and the rate at which your classifier is making false alarms (False Positives or FP). We will use a generalized linear models (Just to change the linear model)

for more informations check this : ROC Curves in Python and R
